ree">2</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Co-author cited on Tibetan monasticism.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="P_MILAREPA"><data key="node_label">Milarepa</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">28</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Paradigmatic Tibetan yogin and disciple of Marpa whose life became the central Kagyu exemplar of hardship, realization, and song transmission.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="P_NAGARJUNA"><data key="node_label">Nagarjuna</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">22</data><data key="node_presetTags">kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Foundational Madhyamaka authority repeatedly invoked in lamrim, ethics, and Tsongkhapa’s interpretation of the middle way.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="P_NAROPA"><data key="node_label">Naropa</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">41</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Indian mahasiddha and former Nalanda scholar-abbot, disciple of Tilopa, and key source for the Six Yogas and Kagyu tantric transmission.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="P_NAWANG"><data key="node_label">Nawang Tsering</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">2</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Author of the monograph.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_PER_0049"><data key="node_label">Ngari Rinpoche</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">0</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Abbot of Likir, brother of the Dalai Lama</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_PER_0050"><data key="node_label">Ngawang 