siddha figure with whom Great Kagyu Masters associates Marpa as a manifestation.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0027"><data key="node_label">Rechungpa</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">9</data><data key="node_presetTags">kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Close disciple of Milarepa and transmitter of the Rechung aural lineage within Kagyu.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0029"><data key="node_label">Zhabdrung Ngawang Namgyel</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">8</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Seventeenth-century Drukpa master whose flight to Bhutan led to the formation of the Bhutanese Drukpa branch and state.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0030"><data key="node_label">Phajo Drukgom Zhikpo</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">5</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Early Drukpa master active in Bhutan before the seventeenth century, associated with establishing Drukpa institutions there.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0031"><data key="node_label">Drukpa Künlé</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">6</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Famous Drukpa yogin active in Bhutan before the seventeenth century, remembered for unconventional sanctified conduct.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0032"><data key="node_label">Kumaradza</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">10</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Nomadic Nyingthig lineage-holder and Longchenpa’s root guru, who received and transmitted the Vima Nyingthig teachings.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0033"><data key="node_label">Samantabhadra</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">10</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Primordial buddha of the Great Perfection, invoked as the all-good reality and spontaneous luminous awareness.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0034"><data key="node_label">Vimalamitra</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">7</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Indian Great Perfection master whose Vima Nyingthig transmissions form a core branch of Longchenpa’s lineage.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0035"><data key="node_label">Yeshe Tsogyal</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">5</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Principal Tibetan disciple of Padmasambhava and transmitter/concealor of Nyingthig teachings important to Longchenpa’s lineage.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0036"><data key="node_label">Aryadeva</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">3</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Disciple of Nagarjuna and early Madhyamaka authority praised by Tsongkhapa as a clarifier of the good path.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0037"><data key="node_label">Buddhapalita</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">4</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Indian Madhyamaka commentator praised by Tsongkhapa for illuminating Nagarjuna’s final intent.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PER_0038"><data key="node_label">Bhavaviveka</data><data key="node_category">Person</data><data key="node_degree">4</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Indian Madhyamaka philosopher associated with the Svatantrika branch that Tsongkhapa distinguishes from Chandrakirti’s reading.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_PLA_0018"><data key="node_label">Sangphu Neutog</data><data key="node_category">Place</data><data key="node_degree">1</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Important Tibetan monastic college where Longchenpa studied for six years after leaving Samye.</data><data key="node_lat">29.73</data><data key="node_lon">91.34</data></node><node id="EXT_PLA_0019"><data key="node_label">Yartö Khyam</data><data key="node_category">Place</data><data key="node_degree">2</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Region or encampment where Longchenpa met his root guru Kumaradza in 1335.</data><data key="node_lat">31.2</data><data key="node_lon">90.8</data></node><node id="EXT_PLA_0020"><data key="node_label">Tashi Gang</data><data key="node_category">Place</data><data key="node_degree">2</data><data key="node_presetTags">kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Place where Milarepa was teaching when Gampopa finally met him, according to later Kagyu biographies.</data><data key="node_lat">27.3333</data><data key="node_lon">91.55</data></node><node id="EXT_PLA_0021"><data key="node_label">Bumthang</data><data key="node_category">Place</data><data key="node_degree">1</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Bhutanese region associated with Longchenpa’s exile and later activities in the Longchenpa biographies.</data><data key="node_lat">27.5497</data><data key="node_lon">90.7525</data></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0001"><data key="node_label">Bon</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">19</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Indigenous/shamanic tradition in Tibetan religious history.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0002"><data key="node_label">Chang 'Brug</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">0</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Northern branch associated with Hemis/Stagtshang Repa.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0003"><data key="node_label">Drigungpa Kargyu</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">14</data><data key="node_presetTags">kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Sub-branch represented at Lamayuru.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="T_DRUKPA"><data key="node_label">Drukpa</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">74</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Drukpa Kagyu lineage central to Hemis, Stagna, Dzongkul, Gotsang and allied contexts, later split into northern (Tibetan/Ladakhi) and southern (Bhutanese) branches.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0005"><data key="node_label">Geluk</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">50</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Reformed school central to scholastic philosophy and ethics.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0006"><data key="node_label">Kadampa</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">16</data><data key="node_presetTags">kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Celibate order associated with Atisa and Gampopa's synthesis.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="T_KAGYU"><data key="node_label">Kagyu</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">105</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa; kagyu</data><data key="node_description">Lineage descended from Tilopa/Naropa/Marpa/Milarepa/Gampopa.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="T_BUDDHISM_LADAKH"><data key="node_label">Ladakhi Buddhism</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">0</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Regional form of Himalayan Buddhism in the study.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0008"><data key="node_label">Lho 'Brug</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">0</data><data key="node_presetTags">drukpa</data><data key="node_description">Southern branch associated with Bhutan and Stagna inheritance.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0010"><data key="node_label">Nyingma</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">33</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">Tibetan Buddhist school associated with Dzogchen and Tragthog.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="YOL_TRA_0011"><data key="node_label">Ri-me</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">10</data><data key="node_presetTags" /><data key="node_description">Non-sectarian eastern Tibetan movement shaping Tipun lineage.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_TRA_0001"><data key="node_label">Sakya</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">24</data><data key="node_presetTags">nyingma</data><data key="node_description">One of the major schools of Tibetan Buddhism.</data><data key="node_lat" /><data key="node_lon" /></node><node id="EXT_TRA_0005"><data key="node_label">Shangpa Kagyu</data><data key="node_category">Underpinning</data><data key="node_degree">2</data><data key="node_presetTags">kagyu</